<p>This conditional code execution if statement is right out of the php manual:</p>  <pre><code>// version_compare ( string $version1 , string $version2 [, string $operator ] ) // http://php.net/manual/en/function.version-compare.php if (version_compare(PHP_VERSION, '5.3.0') &gt;= 0) {     //echo 'I am at least PHP version 5.3.0, my version: ' . PHP_VERSION . "\n";     include_once( DOMAIN_PATH . "sitewide/functions/make_comparer.php" );     usort($market_and_volume, make_comparer(['exchange_volume', SORT_DESC], ['exchange', SORT_DESC]));    } </code></pre>  <p>The above code runs free of error on the production server. On localhost php version 5.2.9-2 which theoretically fails the version_compare() function it throws an error:</p>  <p>Parse error: parse error, expecting `')'' in test.php on line 61</p>  <p>Normally i might not care since its running on the 5.4.39 production server, however I plan to use this snippet on almost every localhost page which as it stands would impede future development.</p>  <p>Any ideas?</p>